segments.text: I'm sitting in the beautiful sunroom at 305 East Brookside in Bryan with Lannis Hope, a long-time faculty colleague.
Now we're going to stop and be sure the machine is working.
And didn't get it on there that this is October 12.
Lannis, would you give us a brief biographical background
before we chat about your years here as a member of the faculty and the staff.
Okay, I was born out in West Texas in Motley County, a little town called Roaring Springs.
My father was a farmer and he had worked as a cowhand for the Matador Ranch in that county there.

But his father had a good bit of land and had come from southern parts of Texas and earlier his father, my grandfather, had run away from home in Tennessee and came to Texas and was working in the cotton field south of Dallas.
at age 14, when he finally got married to my grandmother there in those counties south of Dallas in Waxahachie.
But ultimately, they came out to West Texas.
They were still farming out there.
And I was born there in 1921.
But shortly, my father left the farm and went to work for the railroad for the rest of his life.
And I grew up with my five brothers and sisters in the town of Slaton, Texas, just about 15 miles outside of Lubbock, now a bedroom community for Lubbock.
And went to high school there with the exception of my last year in high school when I went away from home and went and lived with a schoolteacher in Borger, Texas.
The school teacher was a sort of a mentor for me and I was his live-in babysitter for his family for my last year.
Then I went to Texas Tech for one year and at the end of that year the shadows of World War II were long and so I joined the National Guard to be mobilized as federal troops in 1940.
five years in the service, and I came out and in the process I met my wife, married her, went overseas for two years in the European theater.
Came home and spent about a year in business with my father-in-law, and then decided I'd go back to college and make a school teacher.
Went to Texas Tech at Lubbock, my hometown, essentially.
And finished my degree and started teaching in the Lubbock public schools.
But then a set of circumstances caused me to decide to go on to graduate school.
And I went to graduate school and took a psychology, counseling psychology major at the University of Texas.
After that, I worked for Baylor for 10 years as assistant dean of men.
And I came to A&M in 1961.
Been there ever since.
Describe the process of you and A&M meshing.
How did you know there was a vacancy?
Who recruited you?
Well, Austin Curley recruited me.
Actually, he recruited me the year before I came.
And I was ABD at Texas, and I decided I wouldn't take another job until I finished the dissertation.
So the next year when I'd finished, the position was still open at A&M as a counselor.
And so I took it the second time around.
At that time, counselors in the Counseling Center had academic rank.
And I taught one course.
In the Department of?
In the Department of Education.
And then the Department of Education and Psychology.
They put both names in there at the time.
That's another story.
So they made me assistant professor in education and a counselor in the Counseling and Testing Center.
We had offices in Old Aggieland Inn.
First two floors, I think.
Which, just tell us.
until west of Spiesa Dining Hall, about a five, six story building.
The top floors were unused because they were not inhabitable.
And it was the, I guess you'd say it was the student center before the present.
at the center of Loganville in about 1952.
It had once been a kind of an overnight hotel, had it not?
It was a hotel, in every sense of the word.
And many parents of the students I counseled would come in to see me there and say, I spent my first wedding night here, or whatever else like that.
And they remembered it as the MSC.
Describe your duties in that new job.
I was counseling, mostly academic and vocational counseling for six, seven thousand male students that came to A&M at the time.
There was, there were two other half-time counselors and a couple of people who were involved in teaching courses.
The Counseling Center was charged with teaching what they call basic courses.
These were left over from the old basic division.
And they gave academic credit for taking a course in vocational guidance or a course in personal development or a course in architecture, anything introductory type of courses.
So I'd end up teaching some of those courses and how to study and how to
pass courses and stuff like that.
And along with teaching a straight academic course over in the education department, I taught child psychology and adolescent psychology over there.
So did you teach two courses every semester?
No, one course every semester.
One academic course, three hour, plus I would take another of the one hour basic courses.
By and large, what were you primarily counseling these students about?
Mostly career choice.
However, because I was the only PhD level counselor, I ended up with all of the personal counseling cases at that time.
And I was hired mostly to do that kind of thing.
I also visited the hospital daily for the people who had breakdowns and whatever at the hospital.
And I would go over there and check with those people who had been hospitalized every day.
Describe the range of the kinds of, and in general, can you give any examples of some of the most typical counseling problems?
Well, a lot of people came for careers.
And their problem with careers mostly was the same ones we have today.
in that they find themselves signed up for a career which is inappropriate to their interests.

It may be because their sweetheart or their father or their doctor or their pastor sort of influenced them to choose this career, and they were having trouble changing their mind and getting out of it.
And also about that time, research had been published which indicated that rarely were 18- and 19-year-olds mature enough
to make a final decision.
So they had a perfectly sound basis for their indecision.
And it was just a matter of getting through there.
I counseled quite a few corps.
Of course, it was all corps the first year or two I came.
Everybody except transfer students were in corps.
About 5,000, I would guess, something like that.
And I was a

a listening ear for a lot of trouble, some of them inconsequential, some of them pretty consequential, about how to get along in the Corps and how to get along with their buddies and what to do and what not to do and stuff like that.
And I guess one of the really puzzlers for me was one cadet who was on the military scholarship and was deep into Corps activities, which involved a lot of the
what was then called hazy, and they said, man, I want to be in the Army, but this is not what I thought the Army was like.

And so I had to bring them around to some adjustment to the, either realizing that they couldn't put up with this or else they had to put up with it until they get through and the real Army wouldn't be like this quite.
A lot of those things varied back and forth there.
A lot of boy-girl problems.
Of course, the girls weren't here, but the more girl problems were there nevertheless.
You didn't mention financial problems.
Didn't have too much to do with financial at that time.
Oh, okay.
We didn't have the, A&M didn't have the vast amount of student aid on the books at that time.
that they have now.
And so people came, they were pretty much on their own.
They had to do it.
There wasn't a matter of finding university funds or scholarship funds or stuff like that.
Can you share some general anecdotes about examples of some unusual situations you worked on?
Of course, mentioning no names.
Oh, I think of one, a counselee I saw a half dozen times.
he got out a pencil and a pad of paper and started sketching me.
And I could see what was going on.
I didn't raise an eyebrow, I just let it go.
And when he left that day, he came to give me the picture.
A pretty good likeness of me.
Very good.
Did he sign it?
Yeah, he signed it, yeah.
Okay.
And he didn't end up to be a famous artist?
No, he didn't end up to be a famous artist, no.
What in general
Did these conferences with these students lead you to any opinion about the Corps of Cadets' role at A&M?
Oh, that's a good question.
I don't think I realized when I took the job that the military interfaced as pervasively as it did.

But I remember also one of the questions asked me when I was interviewing for the job, the department head asked me, he says, now, in your role as a reserve officer, you don't intend to wear your uniform and come to the class and lecture in your uniform, do you?
I mean, the fact that he could ask that question even indicates that there was some
attitude on the part of faculty that they wondered about the military business.

But my military rank never entered into anything that I ever did with students, except to, as I said just a while ago, try to assure them that the real Army was really not like the Cadet Corps and any other military school.
You go through a phase there, and then you go out into a career that's not exactly like that.
Not that the principles they teach, duty, honor, and what have you like that, that's okay.
I'm in favor of all of that.
This doesn't interfere with that at all.
Now, administratively, you were reporting to, where did your unit fit administratively?
It really didn't have much of a home.
Someday, when you interview Austin Curley, you can talk to him about where we fit in there.
We were called the Counseling and Testing Center.
We had been, shortly before I came, two or three years, it had been a whole division.
Indeed, they called it a basic division, which is a group of college, and they had a dean.
So it still had a good deal of academic clout, and that's the reason that all counselors had faculty rank, because of the holdover from the time when it was a basic division.
There was no dean of instruction.
I think Dean Frank Hubert sort of informally was our supervisor, so he was dean of arts and sciences.
Y'all were not part of...
the Dean of Students, Dean Hannigan's operation.
No.
Nor Mr. Heaton's.
Right.
We're completely separate from those.

Did this lead you, as discussion began to break out in the early 60s about whether or not the Corps might be non-compulsory and women admitted, did your experiences as a counselor lead you to have any opinions about those matters?
No, not really.
I honestly can't say that I had any feeling other than I truly believed in the volunteer concept and the citizen army.
I got that because I went into the army as a private and went through OCS.
And having served as a private,
and seen a lot of citizen soldiers and citizen officers in five years I was in the service.
And I had seen that they were every bit as good as the academic graduates, in some cases better.
And the fact that I just didn't believe in a huge professional army.
So in that sense, I really believed in volunteerism, being in the cadet corps.
When I was a freshman at Texas Tech, I was in the OTC.
I immediately joined because I felt I wanted to be a part of it.
So that's where I come from.
I didn't think very much about it being compulsory or non-compulsory.
I just accepted that as part of A&M and I came.
It is and that's what I work with.
Did you have, did you come to have any feeling about it being, the institution being all male?
Yep.
As a psychologist, I could not see that as useful for many reasons.
But I thought co-education was really the proper way to have an education.
Did, as you counseled with these young men,
Was the corps and of the all-male status, were those sometimes part of their problems?
The fact that this was an all-male institution, was that sometimes a problem, and that their girl was a long way away, and or that they didn't want to be in the corps?
That's part of it, yes.
I think, and there wasn't as much transportation in those days as there is now.
Even in 61, not everybody had wheels like they have today.
And yeah, I felt that that exchange was necessary for our healthy psychological growth and personal development.
Let's talk about some of the key personalities then.

uh the dean hennigan uh generalize about him dean hennigan came very near the same time i came as i remember that and he was a of course a west pointer and made points there but he thoroughly accepted
A&M and all of its traditions.
And even when we went through the transition to non-military, he was supportive all the way through.
Was he supportive?
Dean Hannigan, I didn't have too much contact with him at that time because he was
in the position of student life.
And as you see, we were academically oriented, so we didn't have much to do with his office at all.
All right, what about a young man named Lloyd Heaton?
Lloyd Heaton, the registrar.
We didn't have any direct contact with him.
Okay.
Oh, I'm sorry.
No.
Frank Hubert.
Frank Hubert, of course, was the Dean of Arts and Sciences

eventually became five different colleges but he was very sympathetic with us because he had been a public school man and he was hard as everything on us the first Christmas we were here just before Christmas the counseling and testing center sent out a communication to all high school counselors in the state and we were working pretty hard in those days we were working at
50-hour week for sure, and we did supervise, proofread a letter that went out to the whole house.
And he said, plain geometry, P-L-A-I-N.
So one of Dean Hubert's colleagues out in the public groups immediately contacted him.
So we were on the carpet the day before Christmas, and we spent Christmas rewriting that and writing an apology to all high school students.
And he didn't have any direct supervision of us, but he said, we can't afford to have this kind of image go out to the high school counselors of A&M.
It's bad enough already.
Now, I didn't know what he meant by bad enough already, but I was soon to learn, I think, that we didn't enjoy a good reputation among high school students or their parents in the state at the time.
All right, the chief academic officer then was Wayne Hall.
The graduate dean.
And did you have any description you can offer about him?
Didn't have any contact with him.
Okay.
That fall, first fall, they hired a dean of instruction and he became our boss.
Who was that?
And his name was, I'm blocked on it, I'll take it in just a minute.
He was in our church down there.
Bill Graff?
Bill Graff.
They hired him that fall and we didn't even know he was coming until we saw an article
Eagle, Brian Eagle.
Bill Graff was coming as Dean of Instruction and we were placed under him from then on and that ended Dean Hubert's informal supervision of us.
I think that's what happened.
Describe Dean Graff's manner or style.
He was uninformed about counseling and testing and
not be a professional military man, except for a very short while.
He had a surprisingly military approach to most things.
But he was pretty authoritarian in his approach to the whole campus.
All right.
Now, you and I then worked for the same president for close to a decade.
Describe your impressions of Earl Rudder.
Well, what I just said about Bill Graff using the unpleasant military aspects in his relationship with people, I'd have to say the exact opposite of Earl Rutter.
I had a good deal of personal contact with him even before I came because I was in his army reserve unit.
And so although he was a general and I was a captain,
still you see and hear of him a lot for two weeks every summer when we go to camp.
So I knew him slightly and then they appointed me to the faculty athletic council about two or three years there.
And as such being on that with that body I had we dealt a lot with Earl and him and other
other schools.
So I got to know him there.
I'll never forget.
He called me down before he approved my appointment to the Athletic Council, which I hardly knew what it was.
They only took me on there because of my expertise in test and measurements.
And the Athletic Council was charged with developing a formula which would predict grade point ratio for incoming athletes.
And it had to be at least 1.6.
prediction before they could be recruited.
Now is that 1.6 as we now compute it?
Does that translate to 1.6 today?
Yes, as it is today.
A&M being on a three-point system, it was a .6.
And so I had an interesting research project that lasted for two, three years there, but before he accepted me, he called me down to the office at the system building.
He said,
Landy says, what do you want to do this for?
I said, well Chris Gronemann took me on to consult on some things and I went on a trip or two with him and if he wants me I'll be glad to work with him any way I can.
He said, okay.
So I was in, but then I was in his home several times in that
office, the other five or six members of the Athletic Council, and we got to know him.
They were from West Texas, of course, and they even knew Peggy's folks.
Sort of casual acquaintance, knew who they were and stuff like that.
But yeah, I have nothing with the highest respect for him, and he was not
blood and guts kind of military man at all.
Describe him physically.
What size man was he?
He was over six feet and he weighed about 215, 20 pounds and he got to be overweight for a while and he tried his best to play golf and he would play and
Marvin Tate would try to get him out of the office.
And invariably, he'd go over there when they had a date to play golf and something happened that he could not come.
Literally, I was a pretty close observer of his 10 years of service and his 10 years which undermined his health, which eventually cost him his life, because I could see him going down physically.
And he wasn't very old either.
He got through his retirement, he died shortly before his retirement came into force.
He was 59 years old.
One month before his 60th birthday.
We all grieved because he didn't get that.
Could you see his health declining?
Oh yes, I think that was visible.
Not mentally, but physically he was...
softer and breathing hard and stuff like that.
Could you tell any difference in his work schedule?
No.
He worked hard if not harder.
It was pretty hard on him adjustment wise.
There was a lot of opposition to him on the non-military and the co-ed stuff.
And there was one
Board of Regents meeting, which we were called to.
And some of the regents were late getting there and they were all sitting around the table and the meeting was held over in the meeting room in Svisa Dining Hall.
They didn't have a place on the campus, no rudder tower or anything like that at the time.
And I never, of course, the Athletic Council was sitting around the back side
with a room like that and your sort of supernumerary, but it was about the eligibility of the 1.6 rule and all that sort of stuff.
They were there to tell them what was going on.
And while we're in this informal period there, I'd have to say that the regents, in a good-natured way, were harassing him about
for education and anything else.
Student fees.
Was this before it had happened?
No, it was afterwards.
Oh, afterwards.
Afterwards.
And one of the main contentions there was, why can't we raise this student service fee?
And he didn't want to raise it.
And they were harassing him.
But I say good natured.
There was a subtle undertone there, you can't tell what it was going on.
But he kept his cool.
He did not respond to their jibes and barbs at him.
And by the way, one day recently I was talking to Margaret Rutter and told her of this incident.
And she was surprised.
She said, well I would have thought he had flared back at him and shoot him out.
He probably knew who the commanding officers were.
Yeah, he probably did.
Do you have any insight you can share about the deliberations, discussion, steps toward non-compulsory corps, admission of women?
No, I was not party to the detailed discussion.
I didn't get in on that at all.
It was a sort of a surprise to me as I look back on it and think about it now.
My own family almost disowned me when I came here because I had two daughters and a wife who wanted to go to school.
And they thought they could not go to school.
But jobs were hard to find in those days.
You may know about that.
Do you remember, what was your first monthly salary here as you started?
Do you remember that one?
Mine was $5.50.
let's see, I believe I was hired for about $8,000.
So that'd be $750.
Yeah, something like that.
Mine two years earlier was $550 a month in the history department.
But you know, Haskell, what amazed me is that position stayed open for a year.
And nobody would take it.
And it was there for me the next year when I came around and looked at it again.
That says to me that
Not many people were looking at A&M as a desirable place to come.
You and I talked about that before.
Alright, can you share some examples that you may know of of Mr. Rutter's leadership?
Something that he stood up for?
Don't know directly, except the one I observed there where he defended the students not raising their activities fee.
That's the only one I know of right now, directly.
Did you see him much around the campus?
Not that much.
I saw him a lot more because I was on this committee, more than an ordinary prof would see him.
In athletics, as far as you know, in that era, who was calling the shots?
Who was running it?
The council and the president.
